        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Memphis</placeName>
                <date>July 16 1862</date>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>!</p>
            <p>Dear Sir! At last I can give you again<lb/> some information. I have been all the
                time<lb/> well, though suffered much anxiety during<lb/> this war. You must have
                heard already that<lb/> I had a law suit with the congregation where<lb/> I am
                engaged, and that I beat them in the<lb/> first case, and hope to beat them in the
                second<lb/> for libel, as soon when the courts will be open<lb/> again—they reckoned
                behind the host those<lb/> reformers. I had three counsels employed and<lb/> so had
                they, the case lasted three and half<lb/> day—it was hotly contested by them, but
                they<lb/> knew they had little chance, it was very<lb/> interesting. In order to get
                rid of me they accused<lb/> me, that whereas my brother had opened a wholesale<lb/>
                provision store and <sic>commisary</sic> business and used<lb/> my name is the firm
                    (<persName role="author">Jacob J. Peres</persName> &amp; Co.) and whereas<lb/>
                he had op<add>?</add> his store on <add>?</add>. I had<lb/> violated the
                    <date>Shabbath</date>. My plea was, firstly to<lb/>
                <sic>shew</sic> (by <add>שלחן ערוך</add> etc) the invalidity of the charge<lb/> and
                secondly, that malice was the cause of the<lb/> charge, especially my being opposed
                to reform. They<lb/> never dreamed that I could give them such good</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>blows, especially that the Lord had given me fully<lb/> a good living, and I could
                cope with them in any<lb/> way, a poor man had to yield to their machinations.<lb/>
                You know I have given <hi rend="underline"><persName>Wise</persName></hi> a thorough
                thrashing twice<lb/> in the appeal papers, called, him a notorious infidel<lb/>
                author, have put him on the same level with <persName>Schöneman<lb/> Patt</persName>
                from <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> and <persName>Theodore Parker</persName>.
                Do you recollect<lb/> I told you once, to beat them you must give them hard<lb/>
                blows—without mercy—well dear friend I will again<lb/> labor as much I can in our
                common cause,—I have<lb/> started at once a new orthodox Congregation, had<lb/> it
                chartered, we number 55 members, and<lb/>
                <sic>gess</sic> what name I gave it, just <sic>gess</sic>........<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Beth El Emeth</hi>—in honor of the minister of the<lb/>
                Franklin Synagogue in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p>We had a Hazan <persName>Marcuson</persName>—you know him, he<lb/> is a
                    <add>למדן</add>, but is <add>משגע</add> and drinks—hence our<lb/> first trouble;
                please insert the following<lb/> advertisement.</p>
            <p>Wanted, By the Congregation <hi rend="underline">Beth El Emeth</hi>,
                    <placeName>Memphis<lb/> Tenn.</placeName> Immediately a 'Hazan and Sho'het &amp;
                Bal Horah, None<lb/> but fully competent need to apply. Salary <del>from $600</del><lb/>
                <del>to</del> $800.00/100 per annum, besides perquisites. <sic>testimonials</sic>,
                and for <sic>farther</sic><lb/> particulars, address to<lb/></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>L. Alexander</persName>. Prest.<lb/>or <persName
                    role="author">Jacob. J. Peres</persName>. Secy.</p>
            <p>Jewish message copy and bill<lb/> to the Occident.</p>
            <p>Please if possible recommend as a truly competent</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>man—if suitable to the Congr. his salary will be increased.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You must send me my bill I owe you for some<lb/>
                <add>תפלות</add> yet.</p>
            <p>I will send you this or next week the Fifth<lb/> of the articles why do we hide it, I
                was very<lb/> glad that it was so approved of, I received some<lb/> complementary
                letters about it from <placeName>New York</placeName>.<lb/> please if possible send
                me the papers containing<lb/> these articles.</p>
            <p>Hoping to hear from you soon I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Respectfully yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Jacob J. Peres</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
